Day 3: OSI Model and TCP/IP Model

Layers of the OSI (Open Systems Interconnection) Model

There are 7 layers to the OSI model:


Application
Presentation
Session
Transport
Network
Data Link
Physical


The acronym I like to use to remember this — which I actually got from Jason Dion's Network+ study guide — is:


Please Don't Throw Sausage Pizza Away



Every first letter of each layer name is made into that acronym. I love pizza, so this one stuck with me.

Data can move up and down the layers, which is called encapsulation and de-encapsulation. When interaction occurs on the same layer, it's called same-layer interaction.


Encapsulation — data moves from the top layer downward. For example, data moves from the Application layer down to the Presentation layer, and so on.
De-encapsulation — the exact opposite. Data moves upward on the OSI model, from Physical to Data Link, then Data Link to Network, and so on.


What Does Each Layer Do?

Starting at the top, Layer 7, and moving down — kind of like encapsulation:

Layer 7 – Application

This is what you see on the computer screen — what the end user interacts with.

Some protocols at Layer 7 include: HTTP, HTTPS, FTP, SFTP, SMTP, SNMP, to name a few.

Layer 6 – Presentation

This is where the data gets encoded into the proper format to be sent over the network.

Layer 5 – Session

Starts, stops, and restarts communication sessions between applications.

Layer 4 – Transport

Provides end-to-end communication.

DATA + L4 Header

This is called a Segment.

Layer 3 – Network

Provides logical addressing (IP addresses). Provides connectivity between end hosts on different networks, outside of the LAN.


Routers operate at Layer 3.



DATA + L4 Header + L3 Header

This is called a Packet.

Layer 2 – Data Link

Provides node-to-node connectivity and data transfer (for example, PC to switch, switch to router, router to router).


Detects and (possibly) corrects Physical (Layer 1) errors.
Uses Layer 2 addressing, separate from Layer 3 addressing.



Switches operate at Layer 2.



L2 Trailer + DATA + L4 Header + L3 Header + L2 Header

This is called a Frame.

Layer 1 – Physical


Converts raw digital data into physical signals and transmits them across a network.
Basically anything physical: NICs, cables, devices — anything hardware.


